Experiment 2: Distance-Based Servo Motor Control

Description:
This experiment combines an HC-SR04 ultrasonic sensor with an SG90 servo motor.
The ultrasonic sensor continuously measures the distance between the sensor and an object.
Based on the measured distance, the Arduino adjusts the angle of the servo motor to predefined positions.

Components Used:
-Arduino Uno
-HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Sensor
-SG90 Servo Motor
-Breadboard
-Jumper Wires

Code Logic:
The ultrasonic sensor calculates the distance in centimeters and the servo motor
rotates according to the following conditions:

-Distance > 20 cm → Servo moves to 180°
-Distance between 10 cm and 20 cm → Servo moves to 90°
-Distance < 10 cm → Servo moves to 0°

Features:
-Real-time distance measurement.
-Automatic servo positioning based on proximity.
-Demonstrates sensor-to-actuator communication.
-Useful as a basic automated gate or positioning system.

Real-Life Applications:
-Automatic gates and barriers that open or close depending on the presence of a vehicle.
-Smart parking systems that use sensors to detect approaching cars and move gate mechanisms.
-Industrial automation for positioning robotic arms or conveyor mechanisms.
-Touchless dispenser systems where a servo motor controls the release mechanism when a user's hand is detected.
-Smart waste bins that automatically open their lids when someone approaches.